<section xml:id="C14.S27">
<title>Zeros</title>        
  
<para xml:id="C14.S27.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="1" xml:id="C14.S27.p1.s1">
 <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C14.S27.p1.m1">P^{\mu}_{\nu}\left(x\pm i0\right)</Math> (either side of the cut) has exactly one zero in the interval <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C14.S27.p1.m2">(-\infty,-1)</Math> if either of the following sets of conditions holds: <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C14.S27.I1.ix9.p1.m1">\mu&lt;0</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C14.S27.I1.ix9.p1.m2">\mu\notin\mathbb{Z}</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C14.S27.I1.ix9.p1.m3">\nu\in\mathbb{Z}</Math> , and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C14.S27.I1.ix9.p1.m4">\sin\left((\mu-\nu)\pi\right)</Math> and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C14.S27.I1.ix9.p1.m5">\sin\left(\mu\pi\right)</Math> have opposite signs.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="2" xml:id="C14.S27.p1.s2">
<Math mode="inline" xml:id="C14.S27.I1.ix10.p1.m1">\mu,\nu\in\mathbb{Z}</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C14.S27.I1.ix10.p1.m2">\mu+\nu&lt;0</Math> , and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C14.S27.I1.ix10.p1.m3">\nu</Math> is odd.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="3" sentence-num-in-section="3" xml:id="C14.S27.p1.s3">
For all other values of the parameters <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C14.S27.p1.m3">P^{\mu}_{\nu}\left(x\pm i0\right)</Math> has no zeros in the interval <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C14.S27.p1.m4">(-\infty,-1)</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C14.S27.p2">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="4" xml:id="C14.S27.p2.s1">
For complex zeros of <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C14.S27.p2.m1">P^{\mu}_{\nu}\left(z\right)</Math> seeHobson (1931, §§233, 234, and 238).
</sentence>

</para>
 
</section>
